notes.text: An update for NetworkManager is now available for Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7.
notes.title: Topic

notes.text:
NetworkManager is a system network service that manages network devices and connections, attempting to keep active network connectivity when available. Its capabilities include managing Ethernet, wireless, mobile broadband (WWAN), and PPPoE devices, as well as providing VPN integration with a variety of different VPN services.

For detailed information on changes in this release, see the Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7.6 Release Notes linked from the References section.

Users of NetworkManager are advised to upgrade to these updated packages.

cwe.name: Exposure of Sensitive Information to an Unauthorized Actor

notes.text: An information exposure vulnerability has been found in NetworkManager when dnsmasq is used in DNS processing mode. An attacker in control of a DNS server could receive DNS queries even though a Virtual Private Network (VPN) was configured on the vulnerable machine.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: NetworkManager: Information exposure in DNS resolver
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: This issue did not affect the versions of NetworkManager as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5 and 6 as they did not include support for dnsmasq DNS resolver.
notes.title: Statement

notes.text: The CVSS score(s) listed for this vulnerability do not reflect the associated product's status, and are included for informational purposes to better understand the severity of this vulnerability.
notes.title: CVSS score applicability

remediations.details:
For details on how to apply this update, refer to:

https://access.redhat.com/articles/11258
We suggest to keep the default `dns=default` in the NetworkManager configuration file to prevent DNS queries leaks to possibly hostile DNS servers.
